***REPEAT OFFENDER FOR DUI***

DUI# 23-660

Attachments:
MVA Print-Outs
DUI Packet 
Accident Report
Citations

Defendant:
David Njoroge Ndegwa 
3712 W Overlea, Ave
Baltimore, Maryland, 21206
Date of Birth: 12/09/1966
Date of Arrest: 12/23/2023
Time of Arrest: 2144 hours
MD SDX: MD10272806639
  
Certificates and Training
*Trained in administering standardized field sobriety tests through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
*Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement (ARIDE) Certified 
*Certified RADAR/LIDAR operator by the Maryland State Police

VEHICLE WAS INVOLVED IN A CRASH (PHASE 1):
          On Saturday, December, 23rd 2023, at approximately 2114 hours, I, Trooper First Class Thoren #7131, was working routine patrol assigned to the Golden Ring Barrack. The Maryland State Police Golden Ring Duty Officer dispatched me to a motor vehicle collision on the I/L I695 at Exit 33 N/B on-ramp to I95 in Rosedale, Maryland. 

PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2): 
        Once on scene, I TFC Thoren 7131, observed a white Toyota Sienna bearing Maryland registration, “2BA2926.” The Toyota suffered damage from colliding with the concrete barrier. I identified the driver as David Ndegwa (B/M DOB: 12/09/1966), by his Maryland driver’s license. An NCIC/METERS check returned Ndegwa to be driving valid with many points and a history of DUI. Ndegwa's vehicle registration returned as valid. Ndegwa displayed numerous impairment clues such as a very strong odor of an alcoholic beverage, extremely slurred speech, and Ndegwa's own admission of drinking wine prior to driving. I asked Ndegwa where he was trying to go. Ndegwa stated he was trying to go home and almost missed his exit. Ndegwa drove off the road to the left and struck the guardrail end in the gore area between the north and south on-ramp to I95. Ndegwa then lost control of his vehicle and struck the cement barrier on the north I95 ramp. I asked Ndegwa what did he have to drink on multiple occasions, and he finally stated wine. I asked him why did he choose to drive tonight, and he stated he was trying to go home. If Ndegwa was trying to get home from traveling on the Inner Loop, he should've taken exit 32A which is two exits prior to exit 33. Ndegwa kept stating, “be nice to me,” while speaking to him on multiple occasions. I asked Ndegwa multiple times to get out of his vehicle as he kept looking for cigarettes. Ndegwa then tries to put his cigarettes away after being told multiple times that he was not going to smoke a cigarette. Ndegwa kept missing the pocket he kept trying to put his cigarette in. While Ndegwa was exiting his vehicle, he kept trying to fix his vehicle. At this time, I contacted the Maryland State Police Golden Ring Barrack and informed the Emergency Dispatcher that I would be holding Ndegwa out on field sobriety and to send another unit. As I communicated with Ndegwa by the front of my patrol vehicle, I again detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating, even while maintaining more than one arm's length distance from his. Also, while standing in front of my patrol vehicle Ndegwa was saying back and forth, having a hard time keeping his balance. 

PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3): 
The evaluation was performed on the shoulder of the I95 N/B Ramp from I/L I695, Rosedale, Baltimore County, Maryland. The surface was dry, level, and free from any obvious debris. The weather was clear. Lighting conditions consisted of streetlights and vehicle head lamps. 

I asked Ndegwa the following questions: 
Glasses or Contact –No
Medical Conditions – No
Injuries – No  
Medication – No

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (6/6 clues observed) 
      The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. I administered the test per NHTSA standards. The tip of my pen was used as the test's stimulus and held approximately 12 inches from Ndegwa's eyes. Ndegwa was instructed to look straight ahead, keeping his head still while following and focusing on the tip of the stimulus with the eyes until told to stop. Ndegwa pupils were equal in size and showed equal tracking. Ndegwa was positioned in a manner to ensure the headlights of passing traffic would not interfere with the test results. While attempting to complete the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test, Ndegwa had to be told multiple times to both not move his head or to follow the stimulus with his eyes.

Observations: While giving instructions to Ndegwa he kept interrupting me and said, “yes, yes, yes!” And, “After this I go home?” And, “I pass all the tests.” And, “If I pass your test let me go home, my car is not drivable.”
1.) Lack of Smooth Pursuit – Present in both eyes.
2.) Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation – Present in both eyes.
3.) Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees – Present in both eyes.
Vertical Gaze Nystagmus was tested and was observed to be present.

WALK AND TURN (Could not perform)
      Before Ndegwa performed the test, I attempted explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted per NHTSA standards. Ndegwa was instructed to place his right foot directly in front of his left foot and touch heel to toe. Ndegwa was instructed and demonstrated to place his hands flat at his side and to remain in that position until told to begin. 

Observations: Ndegwa interrupts me again while providing instructions and wanted his driver door to be shut. Ndegwa also stated, "I have a problem with my drink." Ndegwa advised me that he promises to not drink again. I advised him that is not how it works, and he needed to complete the tests. Ndegwa stated he could do the test then wanted to try the test then asks if I can take him home. I advised his that I would let him try one more time and if he can not do the WAT test we would move on. I then tried again to explain the test and have Ndegwa to get into the instructional phase, and he stated he couldn’t do the test. 

Walking Stage (1st Nine): Nothing to Report
Walking Stage (2nd Nine): Nothing to report
 
ONE LEG STAND (Could not perform)
Nothing to report. 

ARREST:
Based on the following, I had reason to believe Ndegwa was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol:
*Results from Standardized Field Sobriety Test
*Admission of consuming wine prior to driving
*Extremely Slurred Speech 
*Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from the breath and person 
*Bloodshot and glassy eyes 
*Vehicle Collision
*Ndegwa begged me on numerous occasions to get bring him home, and he would promise not to drink again. 

      At approximately 2144 hours I, TFC Thoren #7131, placed Ndegwa under arrest for driving while under the influence of an alcoholic beverage. Ndegwa was placed in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle per department policy. Ndegwa was transported to the Maryland State Police Golden Ring Barrack for further processing. On at approximately 1024 hours, the DR-15 (Advice of Rights) was read to Ndegwa in English. Ndegwa refused to take the Intoximeter test. Ndegwa was given all copies of his paperwork and was released into the custody of his family friend.

REFUSED THE INTOXIMETER TESTING

ACRS COMPLETED IN THE DELTA PLUS APPLICATION.

Case CLOSED by arrest.

All events occurred in Baltimore County, Maryland.
